acceptable practice, this book debates the practice of collecting ‘difficult’ objects, from a historical and contemporary perspective; and discusses the acquisition of objects related to war and genocide, and those purchased from the internet, as well as considering human remains, mass produced objects and illicitly traded antiquities. The aim is to apply a critical approach to the rigidity of museums in maintaining essentially nineteenth-century ideas of collecting; and to move towards identifying priorities for collection policies in museums, which are inclusive of acquiring ‘difficult’ objects. Much of the book engages with the question of the limits to the practice of collecting as a means to think through the implementation of new strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMuseumsxAcquisitionsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMuseumsxCollection management. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh1 aBardgett, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornish, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurrans, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeisbusch, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, J. C. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, J. C. H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLambert, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLidchi, Henrietta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLohman, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEnroe, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOpie, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearce, Susan, 